Transit-Oriented Development in Washington, DC

Al-Jalil Gault, Master of City Planning, â€™21

Introduction

As 21st century cities continue to grow, they must develop sustainable transportation systems. One strategy to achieve this is to promote Transit-Oriented Development (TOD). TOD involves promoting denser, mixed use development (such as housing, retail, restaurants, hospitals, and other services occupying shared sites) near transit. The goal of TOD is to increase access to these uses by using a cityâ€™s public transportation systems.

This project analyses the nature of development near transit stations in Washington, DC, and makes recommendations for a more sustainable, equitable system.

This study begins by installing libraries, establishing map themes, creating functions, and downloading census data.

# ---- Load Styling options -----

mapTheme <- function(base_size = 12) {
  theme(
    text = element_text( color = "black"),
    plot.title = element_text(size = 16,colour = "black"),
    plot.subtitle=element_text(face="italic"),
    plot.caption=element_text(hjust=0),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(),axis.title = element_blank(),
    axis.text = element_blank(),
    axis.title.x = element_blank(),
    axis.title.y = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    strip.text.x = element_text(size = 14))
}

plotTheme <- function(base_size = 12) {
  theme(
    text = element_text( color = "black"),
    plot.title = element_text(size = 16,colour = "black"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(face="italic"),
    plot.caption = element_text(hjust=0),
    axis.ticks = element_blank(),
    panel.background = element_blank(),
    panel.grid.major = element_line("grey80", size = 0.1),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    strip.background = element_rect(fill = "grey80", color = "white"),
    strip.text = element_text(size=12),
    axis.title = element_text(size=12),
    axis.text = element_text(size=10),
    plot.background = element_blank(),
    legend.background = element_blank(),
    legend.title = element_text(colour = "black", face = "italic"),
    legend.text = element_text(colour = "black", face = "italic"),
    strip.text.x = element_text(size = 14)
  )
}

# Load Quantile break functions

qBr <- function(df, variable, rnd) {
  if (missing(rnd)) {
    as.character(quantile(round(df[[variable]],0),
                          c(.01,.2,.4,.6,.8), na.rm=T))
  } else if (rnd == FALSE | rnd == F) {
    as.character(formatC(quantile(df[[variable]]), digits = 3),
                 c(.01,.2,.4,.6,.8), na.rm=T)
  }
}

q5 <- function(variable) {as.factor(ntile(variable, 5))}

## Geom_line Plot showing mean rent as a function of distance to metro stops
multipleRingBuffer <- function(inputPolygon, maxDistance, interval) 
{
  #create a list of distances that we'll iterate through to create each ring
  distances <- seq(0, maxDistance, interval)
  #we'll start with the second value in that list - the first is '0'
  distancesCounter <- 2
  #total number of rings we're going to create
  numberOfRings <- floor(maxDistance / interval)
  #a counter of number of rings
  numberOfRingsCounter <- 1
  #initialize an otuput data frame (that is not an sf)
  allRings <- data.frame()
  
  #while number of rings  counteris less than the specified nubmer of rings
  while (numberOfRingsCounter <= numberOfRings) 
  {
    #if we're interested in a negative buffer and this is the first buffer
    #(ie. not distance = '0' in the distances list)
    if(distances[distancesCounter] < 0 & distancesCounter == 2)
    {
      #buffer the input by the first distance
      buffer1 <- st_buffer(inputPolygon, distances[distancesCounter])
      #different that buffer from the input polygon to get the first ring
      buffer1_ <- st_difference(inputPolygon, buffer1)
      #cast this sf as a polygon geometry type
      thisRing <- st_cast(buffer1_, "POLYGON")
      #take the last column which is 'geometry'
      thisRing <- as.data.frame(thisRing[,ncol(thisRing)])
      #add a new field, 'distance' so we know how far the distance is for a give ring
      thisRing$distance <- distances[distancesCounter]
    }
    
    
    #otherwise, if this is the second or more ring (and a negative buffer)
    else if(distances[distancesCounter] < 0 & distancesCounter > 2) 
    {
      #buffer by a specific distance
      buffer1 <- st_buffer(inputPolygon, distances[distancesCounter])
      #create the next smallest buffer
      buffer2 <- st_buffer(inputPolygon, distances[distancesCounter-1])
      #This can then be used to difference out a buffer running from 660 to 1320
      #This works because differencing 1320ft by 660ft = a buffer between 660 & 1320.
      #bc the area after 660ft in buffer2 = NA.
      thisRing <- st_difference(buffer2,buffer1)
      #cast as apolygon
      thisRing <- st_cast(thisRing, "POLYGON")
      #get the last field
      thisRing <- as.data.frame(thisRing$geometry)
      #create the distance field
      thisRing$distance <- distances[distancesCounter]
    }
    
    #Otherwise, if its a positive buffer
    else 
    {
      #Create a positive buffer
      buffer1 <- st_buffer(inputPolygon, distances[distancesCounter])
      #create a positive buffer that is one distance smaller. So if its the first buffer
      #distance, buffer1_ will = 0. 
      buffer1_ <- st_buffer(inputPolygon, distances[distancesCounter-1])
      #difference the two buffers
      thisRing <- st_difference(buffer1,buffer1_)
      #cast as a polygon
      thisRing <- st_cast(thisRing, "POLYGON")
      #geometry column as a data frame
      thisRing <- as.data.frame(thisRing[,ncol(thisRing)])
      #add teh distance
      thisRing$distance <- distances[distancesCounter]
    }  
    
    #rbind this ring to the rest of the rings
    allRings <- rbind(allRings, thisRing)
    #iterate the distance counter
    distancesCounter <- distancesCounter + 1
    #iterate the number of rings counter
    numberOfRingsCounter <- numberOfRingsCounter + 1
  }
  
  #convert the allRings data frame to an sf data frame
  allRings <- st_as_sf(allRings)
}

Identifying TOD

Now that we have downloaded Metro Stops, we can determine whoch cenus tracts can be classified as having â€œTransit Oriented Developmentâ€. For the purposes of this study, weâ€™ve defined potential of TOD as development within .5 miles of a Metro Stop.

Because we want to compare multiple variables, weâ€™ve decided to constrain ourselves to consistent â€œUnits of analysisâ€, which will be a Census Tract. If the center of a census tract is within .5 miles of a Metro Station, we will consider that tract as having TOD. If a census tractâ€™s centroid is beyond .5 miles of a Metro Station, we will consider that tract as Non-TOD. One of the drawbacks of this method is that we potentially leave out development near transit that is close to a transit station, and we may inadvertently include data that might be far from transit (even though its census tractâ€™s centroid is close to transit).

#create a .5 mile buffer around Metro Stops.
buffer <- 
    st_union(st_buffer(metroStops, 2640)) %>%
      st_sf() %>%
      mutate(Legend = "Unioned Buffer")

# Determine the 2009 tracts that have their centroid in the buffer
selectCentroids <-
  st_centroid(tracts09)[buffer,] %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  left_join(dplyr::select(tracts09, GEOID)) %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(GEOID, TotalPop) %>%
  mutate(Selection_Type = "Select by Centroids")

#create an outline for TOD tracts
TOD_outline <- st_union(selectCentroids)

#visualize selected tracts
ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data=tracts17, fill="white") +
  geom_sf(data = TOD_outline, size = 1.25, color = "black", fill = NA ) +
  geom_sf(data = buffer, size = .5, color = "red", fill = NA) +
  geom_sf(data=metroStops, 
          show.legend = "point", size= 2) +
  labs(title="Metro Stops", 
       subtitle="Washington, DC") +
  mapTheme()

# We then determine the centroids from the allTracts dataframe, which include data from both 2009 and 2017
# and create a column "TOD" that identifies the tracts that have centroids within the buffer as "TOD" and
# the remaining tracts as "non-TOD"

allTracts.group <- 
  rbind(
    st_centroid(allTracts)[buffer,] %>%
      st_drop_geometry() %>%
      left_join(allTracts) %>%
      st_sf() %>%
      mutate(TOD = "TOD"),
    st_centroid(allTracts)[buffer, op = st_disjoint] %>%
      st_drop_geometry() %>%
      left_join(allTracts) %>%
      st_sf() %>%
      mutate(TOD = "Non-TOD"))

## Analyze daya by distance from a train station.

#establish multi-ring buffers
buffers <- multipleRingBuffer(metroStops, 21120, 1320) #buffer every .25 miles (1,320 ft)

#join census tract data by buffers to assign a tiered distance for every .25 miles (1,320 ft)
allTracts.rings <-
  st_join(st_centroid(dplyr::select(allTracts, GEOID, year)), 
          multipleRingBuffer(st_union(metroStops), 21120, 1320)) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  left_join(dplyr::select(allTracts, GEOID, MedRent, year), 
            by=c("GEOID"="GEOID", "year"="year")) %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  mutate(distance = distance / 5280) #convert to miles

#summarise data to obtain average rent 
allTracts.rings_summary <-
  allTracts.rings %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  group_by(year, distance) %>%
  summarize(Rent = mean(MedRent, na.rm=T)) 

#plot results
ggplot(subset(allTracts.rings_summary, distance < 2.5), aes(x = distance, y = Rent)) + 
  geom_line(size = 1, aes(color = year)) +
  labs(title="Rent as a funtion of Distance to Metro Stations",
       subtitle = "Average rent in Washington, DC; 2009 and 2017") +
plotTheme() + theme(legend.position="bottom")

#join crimes to station buffers
j_crime <- 
  st_join(crime, station_buffer) %>%
  filter(!is.na(NAME))

#summarize crime counts by station
crimeByStation <-
  j_crime %>% 
  group_by(NAME) %>% 
  summarize(crime_count = n())%>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  left_join(metroStops) %>%
  st_sf()

#visualize crime by station and rent
ggplot() + 
  geom_sf(data=tracts17, aes(fill = q5(MedRent)), alpha = .75) +
  geom_sf(data=crimeByStation, aes(size=crime_count), alpha = .5) +
  geom_sf(data = TOD_outline, size = 1, color = "black", fill = NA) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#f1eef6", "#d7b5d8", "#df65b0", "#dd1c77", "#980043"),
                    name = "Median Rent\n(Quintile Breaks)",
                    labels = qBr(allTracts.group, "MedRent")) +
  labs(title="Metro Stops by Number of Crimes \n& Surrounding cost of Rent", 
       subtitle="Washington, DC; 2017",
       size = "Crime\nwithin .5 miles") +
  mapTheme()

Finally, we visualize relationhips between crime, transit, and cost of rent. The most cimes in DC seem to not necessarity be correlated with high rent, but with with populaiton and populaiton density (in accordance with maps presented further above).

We should also beware that crimes from this dataset could be biased. Data show that minority populaitons are twice as likely to be stopped by posice officers in some cases (https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2016/07/data-police-racial-bias). Thus, crimes committed by white people are 50% less likely to be present in this data.

Policy Suggestion

To address this bias and reduce crime at the same time, there are several ways to address crime without increasing police presence or violence. These strategies are from The Urban Institute (https://www.urban.org/urban-wire/five-ways-reduce-crime). Strageties include:

  • Expanding use of drug courts as social service programs to reduce drug use.
  • Make use of DNA evidence
  • Help ex-offenders find secure living-wage employment
  • Monitor public surveillance cameras
  • Connect returning prisoners to stable housing
